{"ts":"2026-06-27T18:22:13.008Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Confirming Functionality Status**\n\nI'm thrilled! The `/api/v1/projects` endpoint is confirmed as fully operational. Excellent news! Now, I am verifying whether `/api/v1/auth/login` and `/api/v1/auth/me` are also functioning correctly, because I recall them working in the other admin pages. Finally, I'll go to the admin page related to documents.\n\n\n**Defining Document Workflow**\n\nI've outlined the document fetching and formatting sequence for the admin page. On page load, I'll grab the auth token then retrieve documents from the `/api/v1/documents` endpoint. The documents will be mapped into `DocumentItem` format, including fields such as `id`, `title`, `fileSize`, `status`, and so on. Additionally, I've decided to statically map client IDs to their names, avoiding an unnecessary API call.\n\n\n**Refining Data Fetching Strategy**\n\nI'm now refining the data fetching strategy for projects. Initially, I thought about keeping static arrays for clients and projects if IDs matched. However, I've decided to dynamically fetch projects from `/api/v1/projects`, adding resilience by falling back to a static list if the fetch fails. I'm building a `fetchData` function with token retrieval and a call to the projects endpoint. I have to check if `/app/admin/documents/page.tsx` uses `PROJECTS` for display or dropdowns, and ensure dynamic loading integrates seamlessly.\n\n\n**Establishing API Connectivity**\n\nI've crafted a `fetchData` function to streamline token acquisition and project retrieval. It starts by attempting a login with hardcoded credentials to get a token and then retrieves the projects, mapping the response to `ProjectItem` objects. A key improvement is the token is now being handled with more robustness, and the login flow has been confirmed. I am now proceeding with the project retrieval and mapping.\n\n\n**Integrating Document Updates**\n\nI've integrated the document fetching and mapping logic. I'm calling `/api/v1/documents` and mapping the response. I'm focusing on ensuring data integrity for each document item, including handling cases where fields like `fileSize`, `type`, and `sha256` are missing. I am also making sure the client ID to name mapping is working, and that I correctly handle the \"UNASSIGNED\" project scenario, and the different fields it could be in.\n\n\n**Optimizing Dynamic Project Handling**\n\nI've just refined my approach for handling project data dynamically. Initially, I declared `PROJECTS` as a constant, but I've updated it to be a React state variable that initializes from a static list. I am now confident this ensures backwards-compatibility while also enabling dynamic population, which gives a far more robust, seamless user experience. I'm now auditing the code to confirm no `useMemo` calls or other static filters depend on this data.\n\n\n**Analyzing CRUD Operations**\n\nOkay, I've confirmed `PROJECTS` is extensively referenced within `/app/admin/documents/page.tsx`! Specifically, there are uses in both the desktop table and mobile cards mapping, and in the select dropdowns, so changing it to `projects` will work well. I am now thoroughly analyzing the CRUD actions necessary for documents and determining the required API calls. I'm focusing on the `POST /api/v1/documents` endpoint and the expected request body, and I'm also reviewing necessary headers.\n\n\n**Implementing Document Updates**\n\nI'm now detailing document creation and modification workflows. For document creation, a successful POST call to `/api/v1/documents` will trigger a refresh or an appends to the document list. A failure will raise an error. Editing uses a PATCH request to the `/api/v1/documents/[id]` endpoint. The request bodies include details like `title`, `status`, and `project_id`. I'm evaluating the client and project synchronizations as well.\n\n\n**Defining State Indicators**\n\nI'm now focusing on implementing state indicators for document management. I'll need `loading`, `empty`, `error`, `success`, and `validation` states for the document registry page. I will show a \"premium scanning\" loading indicator when the document list is loading and handle empty states gracefully. I'm designing these states and how to render them.\n\n\n**Designing State Indicators**\n\nI'm now detailing state indicator implementation for the document registry page, focusing on UI/UX. I am designing states for loading, empty, error, success, and validation, which will enhance document management. I will show a premium scanning loading indicator while documents are being fetched, handle the empty state, and show a success toast on successful operations. I will also incorporate validation for form fields, and am ensuring the design will not break CSS or the existing layout.\n\n\n"}}
